and, United Kingdom":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1270–":"circa 1270–Overleden","1270–Male":"1270–Overleden","1274–Female":"1274–Overleden","1275–Female":"1275–Overleden","1302–1397":"1302–1397","1237–1294":"1237–1294","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1382":"1382","1294":"1294","1270":"1270","Abt 1305":"circa 1305","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1237":"1237","1302":"1302","1301":"1301","1453":"1453","1397":"1397","Abt 1270":"circa 1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Bradenlove, Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1270–":"about 1270–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1274–Female":"1274–Deceased","1275–Female":"1275–Deceased","1302–1397":"1302–1397","1237–1294":"1237–1294","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1382":"1382","1294":"1294","1270":"1270","Abt 1305":"about 1305","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1237":"1237","1302":"1302","1301":"1301","1453":"1453","1397":"1397","Abt 1270":"about 1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Bradenlove, Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moylnes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Moyle  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: in Devon and Cornwall probably a variant of   Mullis  .","Irish (Mayo and Meath): variant of   Miles  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moyle","meanings":["Cornish: probably a nickname from Middle Cornish <i>mōl</i> ‘bald’, though its development to <i>Moyl(e)</i> is irregular.","Welsh: nickname from <i>moel</i> ‘bare, bald’, equivalent to Middle Cornish <i>mōl</i> (see 1 above).","English: variant of   Mule   or   Moule  ."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":45,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":58,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":67,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":112,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"James Moylnes was born about 1270, in Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Wiliam Molyneux. He married Christian Drokenbrode in 1301, in Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in England."},"et":{"Abt 1270–":"umbes 1270–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1274–Female":"1274–Surnud","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1302–1397":"1302–1397","1237–1294":"1237–1294","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1382":"1